    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "We report a case of a 51-year-old man, known to be affected by Mounier-Kuhn Syndrome (MKS), admitted to our accident & emergency (A&E) service of the Baqiyatallah hospital in Tehran (Iran), with a new onset of fever, dyspnea and deterioration of his chronic coughs. On physical examination the patient was ill, febrile, tachycardic, hypoxic with O2 saturation of about 80% and diffuse rhonchi at chest auscultation. The most significant laboratory finding was a notable leukopenia.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Case presentation ::: Introduction",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Chest CT scans revealed increased diameter of his trachea (39 mm), right (30 mm) and left (26 mm) main bronchi, due to MKS. Furthermore, the CT scan showed ground-glass opacities (GGO) and bronchiectasis in the mid and lower zones of both lungs, with small air cysts in the lower zone of the right lung at coronal reconstruction view (Fig1\nA). It also presented ill-defined bilateral GGO and bronchial dilatation within GGO areas bilaterally as well as a small air cyst in the right middle lung lobe at axial images (Fig1B), compatible with an early stage ARDS.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Case presentation ::: Introduction",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 335,
                    "end": 339,
                    "mention": "Fig1",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 517,
                    "end": 521,
                    "mention": "Fig1",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF0"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\nFig. 2\n",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Case presentation ::: Introduction",
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 1,
                    "end": 7,
                    "mention": "Fig. 2",
                    "ref_id": "FIGREF1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In a few hours the patient became cyanotic, with altered mental status, shortage of breath and drop in O2 saturation to about 45%. He was therefore promptly intubated and transferred to the intensive care unit (ICU) for further diagnostic and therapeutic procedures, his clinical and radiological pattern being compatible with ARDS.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Case presentation ::: Introduction",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Although the patient condition was unusual for an early stage of the disease, COVID-19 was still our first differential diagnosis, given we were in the middle of the COIVD-19 epidemic. COIVD-19 infection was eventually confirmed by real time reversed polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR).",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Case presentation ::: Introduction",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "A severe form of COVID-19 could occur even in the early stages, in the presence of an underlying condition as MKS, increasing the susceptibility of the patient to more recurrent and severe respiratory infections.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Case presentation ::: Introduction",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "MKS is a condition more common in men and a rare congenital disorder manifesting with tracheo-bronchial dilation. Although the exact etiology of MKS is unknown,but familial susceptibility and genetic predisposition seem to play a role. MKS is supposedly sustained by lack of musculo-elastic tissue at different levels of the trachea and main bronchi, causing diverticular structures and sacculationar outpouchings especially in the posterior membranous trachea [7,[9], [10], [11], [12]].",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 462,
                    "end": 463,
                    "mention": "7",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                },
                {
                    "start": 464,
                    "end": 467,
                    "mention": "[9]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF8"
                },
                {
                    "start": 469,
                    "end": 473,
                    "mention": "[10]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                },
                {
                    "start": 475,
                    "end": 479,
                    "mention": "[11]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF10"
                },
                {
                    "start": 481,
                    "end": 485,
                    "mention": "[12]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF11"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Discussion",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "The clinical presentations of MKS are not specific and include a wide spectrum of clinical features ranging from asymptomatic or minimal disease with progressive manifestations leading to respiratory failure [13]. Common presentations are chronic productive cough, dyspnea and recurrent respiratory infection due to of mucociliary dysfunction and accumulation of secretions. MKS can also mimic some other cadio-pulmunary diseases such as coronary artery disease, congenital heart disease, congestive heart failure, obstructive airway disease, pneumoconiosis, bronchiectasia and even trombo-embolsim [11,14,15].",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 208,
                    "end": 212,
                    "mention": "[13]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF12"
                },
                {
                    "start": 600,
                    "end": 602,
                    "mention": "11",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF10"
                },
                {
                    "start": 603,
                    "end": 605,
                    "mention": "14",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF13"
                },
                {
                    "start": 606,
                    "end": 608,
                    "mention": "15",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF14"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Discussion",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "COVID-19 can present with mild, moderate and severe symptoms. Whilst most patients develop a mild disease, underlying conditions such as diabetes, hypertension, cardiovascular disorders and malignancies can significantly increase the risk of developing a severe form of COVID-19, especially among patients older than 50 [16,17].",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 321,
                    "end": 323,
                    "mention": "16",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF15"
                },
                {
                    "start": 324,
                    "end": 326,
                    "mention": "17",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF16"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Discussion",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "All possible underlying co-morbidities, even rare conditions as MKS, should be therefore carefully considered when managing a COIVD-19 patient, because they can significantly influence the course of the disease.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
